ce:section.ce:para:
The Hb/GQDs/PG electrode was characterized at various stages of its preparation. CV of the working electrode was performed in acetate buffer (pH 5.0) from a potential range of −1 to + 1 V and at a scan rate of 20 mVs−1(Fig. 4a
                        ). A semi-reversible reaction between Hb-Fe2+ and Hb-Fe3+ has been observed. SEM images showed that the bare PG electrode surface appeared smooth (Fig. 4b.
                        1), while Hb/GQDs were evenly distributed on the PG surface (Fig. 4b.2), suggesting the good biocompatibility of the nanoparticles. By observing (RCT) charge transfer resistance at the electrode and electrolytic contact, the charge transfer process in HbNPs/GQDs/PG electrode was examined (Fig. 4c
                        ). The Warburg diffusion process is represented by the linear portion of the semicircle at lower frequencies, while the semicircle at higher frequencies is associated with the RCT, regulating the electron transfer kinetics at the electrode interface. The EIS of the working electrode is shown in the Nyquist plot in 5 mM K3Fe(CN)6:K4Fe(CN)6 (1:1). The presence of GQDs increased electron transfer through the redox pair on the electrode surface, as evidenced by the lowered RCT value.
